TY  - JOUR
T1  - Role Definitions and Organizational Citizenship Behavior: The Importance of the Employee's Perspective
AU  - Morrison, Elizabeth Wolfe
Y1  - 1994/12/01
PY  - 1994
DA  - 1994/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256798
DO  - 10.5465/256798
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1543
EP  - 1567
VL  - 37
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - A survey of 317 clerical workers demonstrated that employees differed in what they defined as in-role and extra-role behavior, that these differences were related to commitment and social cues, and that employees were more likely to display organizational citizenship behavior (OCB) if they defined the behavior as in-role rather than extra-role. Results indicate that the boundary between in-role and extra-role behavior is not clearly defined and that OCB is a function of how broadly employees define their job responsibilities. This study suggests the need for a reconceptualization of OCB.
AB  - A survey of 317 clerical workers demonstrated that employees differed in what they defined as in-role and extra-role behavior, that these differences were related to commitment and social cues, and that employees were more likely to display organizational citizenship behavior (OCB) if they defined the behavior as in-role rather than extra-role. Results indicate that the boundary between in-role and extra-role behavior is not clearly defined and that OCB is a function of how broadly employees define their job responsibilities. This study suggests the need for a reconceptualization of OCB.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256798
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256798
Y2  - 2026/04/24
