TY  - JOUR
T1  - Board Committee Membership: Effects of Sex-Based Bias
AU  - Bilimoria, Diana
AU  - Piderit, Sandy Kristin
Y1  - 1994/12/01
PY  - 1994
DA  - 1994/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256795
DO  - 10.5465/256795
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1453
EP  - 1477
VL  - 37
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study examined whether female directors lack the necessary experience-based characteristics for board committee membership, or whether there is a systematic sex-based bias against them. We tested predictors of the odds of membership on certain board committees for male and female directors and found evidence of sex-based bias in Fortune 300 firms after controlling for directors' experience-based characteristics. Men were preferred for membership in compensation, executive, and finance committees, and women were preferred for membership in public affairs committees. Implications for the selection of committee members are developed.
AB  - This study examined whether female directors lack the necessary experience-based characteristics for board committee membership, or whether there is a systematic sex-based bias against them. We tested predictors of the odds of membership on certain board committees for male and female directors and found evidence of sex-based bias in Fortune 300 firms after controlling for directors' experience-based characteristics. Men were preferred for membership in compensation, executive, and finance committees, and women were preferred for membership in public affairs committees. Implications for the selection of committee members are developed.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256795
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256795
